<font color="#FF0000">MOVING FORWARD</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 30 21:40:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art,<br><br>
While I do not condone the actions of people against<br>
the returning soldiers. I do think that it is <br>
important to understand that all of us, vets and non-vets<br>
were in a situation that was extreme. In extreme situations<br>
people often do things that are wrong, but understandable.<br><br>
I think one of the tragedies in the war was the inability<br>
of people to seperate the cause of the war and the<br>
people who created and led it with the people who faught<br>
it. It may be difficult to understand, but I think it<br>
is important to do so. <br><br>
I tried a million different ways to end the war, to make<br>
a difference, to bring about peace, because I knew the<br>
war was wrong and people were dying for no good reason.<br>
No matter what I did, the war continued, people died,<br>
whole villages were destroyed, and I could not make it stop.<br><br>
I find it sad that with these discussions, we are not<br>
at a place where we can say with pride and honor that<br>
I was a Vet or I was an anti-war activist and not have<br>
to look over our sholder for the inevitable attack.<br><br>
Now 25+ years after the war I think that it is time to<br>
work on understanding other points of views, and the<br>
actions of others. This leads to the forgiveness and<br>
healing that we need. 
<p><code>-- jproujan@k12s.phast.umass.edu  (Jed Proujansky) </code><p>


